'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ; also written 賀茂神社 / 加茂八幡宮 / 賀茂八幡宮) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} in Irino, {{jalink|Kuroshio|Q1351626}}, {{jalink|Hata District|Q1132241}}, {{jalink|Kochi Prefecture|Q134093}}. It is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}}, and its former rank under the {{jalink|modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|modern system}} was {{jalink|Gōsha|Q134917316}}.

It is the general tutelary shrine of the Irino area, standing inside {{jalink|Irino Pine Grove|Q131912175}}, a nationally designated {{jalink|Place of Scenic Beauty|Q11414752}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The enshrined deities are as follows{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.
* Principal deity: {{jalink|Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|Q11634943|Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto}}
* Co-enshrined deity: {{jalink|Hachiman|Q261637|Hachiman-gū}}
Alternative theories include: {{jalink|Ajisukitakahikone|Q506610|Ajisukitakahikone-no-Kami}} in ''Shingi Shiryo''{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; unknown deity in ''{{jalink|Jinja Kakuroku|Q11590708}}''{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; {{jalink|Ōkamozumi-no-Mikoto|Q106412720}} in ''Tosa no Kuni Shikisha-kō''{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; and Ōkamozumi-no-Mikoto in ''Henkaimatsufu''{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

=== History ===
Foundation is unknown. In the {{jalink|Engi|Q1327274|Engi}} 5 ({{jalink|927|Q30470}}) {{jalink|Engishiki|Q1342448}} {{jalink|Jinmyōchō|Q11064932}}, it is identified with the "Kamo Shrine" listed in {{jalink|Hata District|Q1132241}}, {{jalink|Tosa Province|Q857330}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

According to tradition, Kamo Shrine originally stood at Kamo-yashiki in Irino Honmura, while Hachimangū stood at Hachiman-hara in Hayasaki; the two shrines later became one and moved into Irino Pine Grove{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Tosa no Kuni Shikisha-kō'' also says both shrines were originally in Honmura, though the date of unification is unknown{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Nishiura Kaiken Nikki'' likewise says both were in Honmura{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}.

For the medieval period, tradition says Fujiwara Iemoto revived the shrine around the {{jalink|Ōnin|Q1143903}} era ({{jalink|1467|Q6561}}-{{jalink|1468|Q6564}}){{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Also, the "Irino Ōgata no Gō Chikenchō" of {{jalink|Tenshō|Q1145058}} 17 ({{jalink|1589|Q6759}}) records shrine lands of 5 villages and 3 chō 6 tan in Irino Ōgata-gō{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, during the {{jalink|Hōei earthquake|Q2001581|great Hōei earthquake}} of {{jalink|Hōei|Q1145262}} 4 ({{jalink|1707|Q6841}}), the shrine buildings suffered tsunami damage{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. According to ''Nanroshi'', the shrine buildings floated in floodwater but returned to their original place when the tsunami receded{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}. A monument recording this tsunami damage remains in the precincts{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. In earlier times, Rinzai temple Ōgata-zan Chōsen-ji served as the shrine's {{jalink|bettō-ji|Q11396755}} temple{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

After the {{jalink|Meiji Restoration|Q8707}}, in Meiji 5 ({{jalink|1872|Q7753}}), it was ranked {{jalink|Gōsha|Q134917316}} in the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

