=== History ===
Foundation is unknown. In the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Engi}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470}}) {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932}}, it is identified with the "Kamo Shrine" listed in {{ill|lt=Hata District|Q1132241|WD=Q1132241}}, {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|WD=Q857330}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

According to tradition, Kamo Shrine originally stood at Kamo-yashiki in Irino Honmura, while Hachimangū stood at Hachiman-hara in Hayasaki; the two shrines later became one and moved into Irino Pine Grove{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Tosa no Kuni Shikisha-kō'' also says both shrines were originally in Honmura, though the date of unification is unknown{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Nishiura Kaiken Nikki'' likewise says both were in Honmura{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}.

For the medieval period, tradition says Fujiwara Iemoto revived the shrine around the {{ill|lt=Ōnin|Q1143903|WD=Q1143903}} era ({{ill|lt=1467|Q6561|WD=Q6561}}-{{ill|lt=1468|Q6564|WD=Q6564}}){{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Also, the "Irino Ōgata no Gō Chikenchō" of {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058}} 17 ({{ill|lt=1589|Q6759|WD=Q6759}}) records shrine lands of 5 villages and 3 chō 6 tan in Irino Ōgata-gō{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963}}, during the {{ill|lt=Hōei earthquake|Q2001581|WD=Q2001581|lt=great Hōei earthquake}} of {{ill|lt=Hōei|Q1145262|WD=Q1145262}} 4 ({{ill|lt=1707|Q6841|WD=Q6841}}), the shrine buildings suffered tsunami damage{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. According to ''Nanroshi'', the shrine buildings floated in floodwater but returned to their original place when the tsunami receded{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}. A monument recording this tsunami damage remains in the precincts{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. In earlier times, Rinzai temple Ōgata-zan Chōsen-ji served as the shrine's {{ill|lt=bettō-ji|Q11396755|WD=Q11396755}} temple{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707}}, in Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753}}), it was ranked {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316}} in the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

