[[File:Irino no Matsubara, enkei.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|{{ill|lt=Irino Pine Grove|Q131912175|qid=Q131912175|1=Irino Pine Grove}} (national {{ill|lt=Place of Scenic Beauty|Q11414752|qid=Q11414752|1=Place of Scenic Beauty}})}}]]
'''Kamo Shrine''' (かもじんじゃ; also written 賀茂神社 / 加茂八幡宮 / 賀茂八幡宮) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Irino, {{ill|lt=Kuroshio|Q1351626|qid=Q1351626|1=Kuroshio, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Hata District|Q1132241|qid=Q1132241|1=Hata District, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Kochi Prefecture|Q134093|qid=Q134093|1=Kōchi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=modern system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

It is the general tutelary shrine of the Irino area, standing inside {{ill|lt=Irino Pine Grove|Q131912175|qid=Q131912175|1=Irino Pine Grove}}, a nationally designated {{ill|lt=Place of Scenic Beauty|Q11414752|qid=Q11414752|1=Place of Scenic Beauty}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The enshrined deities are as follows{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.
* Principal deity: {{ill|lt=Kamo Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|Q11634943|qid=Q11634943|lt=Wakeikazuchi-no-Mikoto|1=Kamo-wake-ikazuchi-no-Kami}}
* Co-enshrined deity: {{ill|lt=Hachiman|Q261637|qid=Q261637|lt=Hachiman-gū|1=Hachiman}}
Alternative theories include: {{ill|lt=Ajisukitakahikone|Q506610|qid=Q506610|lt=Ajisukitakahikone-no-Kami|1=Ajisukitakahikone}} in ''Shingi Shiryo''{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; unknown deity in ''{{ill|lt=Jinja Kakuroku|Q11590708|qid=Q11590708|1=Jinja Kakuroku}}''{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; {{ill|lt=Ōkamozumi-no-Mikoto|Q106412720|qid=Q106412720|1=Okamotsumi}} in ''Tosa no Kuni Shikisha-kō''{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}; and Ōkamozumi-no-Mikoto in ''Henkaimatsufu''{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

=== History ===
Foundation is unknown. In the {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|lt=Engi|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}) {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, it is identified with the "Kamo Shrine" listed in {{ill|lt=Hata District|Q1132241|qid=Q1132241|1=Hata District, Kōchi}}, {{ill|lt=Tosa Province|Q857330|qid=Q857330|1=Tosa Province}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

According to tradition, Kamo Shrine originally stood at Kamo-yashiki in Irino Honmura, while Hachimangū stood at Hachiman-hara in Hayasaki; the two shrines later became one and moved into Irino Pine Grove{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Tosa no Kuni Shikisha-kō'' also says both shrines were originally in Honmura, though the date of unification is unknown{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. ''Nishiura Kaiken Nikki'' likewise says both were in Honmura{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}.

For the medieval period, tradition says Fujiwara Iemoto revived the shrine around the {{ill|lt=Ōnin|Q1143903|qid=Q1143903|1=Ōnin}} era ({{ill|lt=1467|Q6561|qid=Q6561|1=1467}}-{{ill|lt=1468|Q6564|qid=Q6564|1=1468}}){{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. Also, the "Irino Ōgata no Gō Chikenchō" of {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 17 ({{ill|lt=1589|Q6759|qid=Q6759|1=1589}}) records shrine lands of 5 villages and 3 chō 6 tan in Irino Ōgata-gō{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, during the {{ill|lt=Hōei earthquake|Q2001581|qid=Q2001581|lt=great Hōei earthquake|1=1707 Hōei earthquake}} of {{ill|lt=Hōei|Q1145262|qid=Q1145262|1=Hōei}} 4 ({{ill|lt=1707|Q6841|qid=Q6841|1=1707}}), the shrine buildings suffered tsunami damage{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. According to ''Nanroshi'', the shrine buildings floated in floodwater but returned to their original place when the tsunami receded{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Heibonsha)|1983}}. A monument recording this tsunami damage remains in the precincts{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}. In earlier times, Rinzai temple Ōgata-zan Chōsen-ji served as the shrine's {{ill|lt=bettō-ji|Q11396755|qid=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}} temple{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|qid=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, in Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was ranked {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in the modern shrine ranking system{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records|1912}}{{Sfn|Kamo Shrine (Shikinaisha)|1987}}.

